node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Recovery and Resilience
.
Everyone is susceptible to invisible wounds. Being able to recognize one of these wounds, and using positive language when discussing it, supports a positive culture across the Department of the Air Force and could save a life. It is important for Airmen and Guardians to seek help for invisible wounds, taking that first step towards recovery.
.
This video describes the importance of Airmen and Guardians seeking help for invisible wounds and how taking that first step towards recovery results in positive outcomes and enhanced resilience.
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Risk, Impact, and Available Resources
.
Over the past five years, United States Department of the Air Force’s Invisible Wounds Initiative has implemented solutions that drive timely, proactive case handling, equitable, informed interactions and decisions, engaged leadership and a supportive environment, and accessible, effective care delivery. 
.
Everyone is susceptible to invisible wounds. The impact of invisible wounds and can develop at any time, in any place, in or out of uniform.
.
Learn more at: https://go.usa.gov/xszpN
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Signs and Symptoms
.
Since its inception in 2016, the United States Department of the Air Force’s Invisible Wounds Initiative has been a leader in creating a supportive culture for #Airmen living with invisible wounds. Being able to recognize an invisible wound could save a life. Airman can learn to see the signs and symptoms of invisible wounds in others that they may see in themselves.
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Charles Q. Brown, Jr., & @cmsaf_official discuss how empowering Airmen will lead to success in building the future Air Force today. They also discussed Accelerate Change or Lose, the Action Orders, leadership and followership, how to rise above bias & self-limitations, and the future of the #AirForce.
.
The primary focus of this call was to connect with Airmen across the world, and give insight to how the Action orders, new Air Force missions statement and developmental guidance are being implemented for the Total Force.
.
#RealTalk #CoffeeTalk #Future #Empowerment #Questions

"Yes hello we've been trying to reach you about your car's extended warranty--"
.
Staff Sgt. Brandon Wood, 56th Civil Engineer Squadron EOD team leader, speaks to a teammate during training at Florence Military Reservation in Florence, Arizona. Wood received a call to remove a simulated explosive vest off of an individual during a day-long training exercise. 

#eod #explosive #training
.
📸 by SSgt Jensen Stidham

node.text:
Rise & grind 💪
.
A Special Mission Aviator from the 41st Rescue Squadron inspects an M2 machine gun during a fini-flight at @moody_afb, Ga. The fini-flight is a long-standing Air Force tradition that occurs when a pilot departs from the base. 
.
#helicopter #flight #aircraft
.
📸 by A1C Eugene Oliver

node.text:
Get after it.
.
Airman, Sailors and Soldiers participate in Sentry Storm 2021. This joint training sharpens the skills needed to prevail over near-peer competitors while applying Agile Combat Employment concepts. Participants include @AirNationalGuard, Army National Guard, Air Force Reserves, @USNavy, Air Force and Civil Air Patrol units. 
.
🎥  by Staff Sgt. Caleb Vance/ edit by Staff Sgt. Elora McCutcheon
.
🎵 Swing Lynn by Harmless
.
#motivation #usmilitary #27videoschallenge

node.text:
The Secretary is in the building!

Today, the Honorable Frank Kendall was sworn into office as the 26th Secretary of the Air Force.

As the top ranking leader of the Department of the Air Force, Kendall is responsible for organizing, training, equipping and ensuring the welfare of nearly 700,000 Airman, Guardians and their families.

@spaceforcedod

Can't call your dad for tips with this oil change 🧰 
.
A maintainer at @travisafb, California, replaces an oil filter on an C-5 Super Galaxy. The C-5M Super Galaxy is the largest aircraft in the Air Force inventory. Its primary mission is to transport cargo and personnel for the Department of Defense.
.

Weather forecast: harsh winds with a chance of sand ⚠️ 
.
Airmen assigned to the 56th Civil Engineer Squadron explosive ordnance disposal team take cover as Army UH-60 Black Hawks take off at the Florence Military Reservation in Florence, Arizona. The team was dropped off by the black hawks during the initial phase of a day-long EOD training exercise.
.
📸 by Staff Sgt. Jensen Stidham

node.text:
In the still of the night 🌆 
.
An MC-130H Combat Talon II assigned to the 15th Special Operations Squadron prepares for flight during a training mission for exercise TRIDENT 18-4 at Hurlburt Field, Florida. The exercise is a United States Special Operations Command sponsored, Naval Special Operations Command executed, joint maritime certification and validation Mission Readiness Exercise which provides realistic and relevant readiness training to U.S. Special Operations Forces, conventional forces, partner forces and inter-argency participants in an irregular warfare scenario. 
.
📸 by Staff Sgt. Corban Lundborg
.
#aircraft #sof @hurlburtfield

node.text:
Showing up in ✨style✨
.
Members with the 919th Special Operations Wing, U.S. Army Special Operations Command Black Daggers, U.S. Army Golden Knights and the U.K. Red Devils Parachute Regiment Display Team participate in the Miami Air and Sea Show in Miami Beach, Florida. The 919th SOW supported the airshow by providing the jump platform for all three parachute demo teams using the C-145A Combat Coyote.
.
🎥 Senior Airman Blake Wiles

node.text:
When the preworkout hits 🏋 
.
Tech. Sgt. Bryan Winterstein, 23d Logistics Readiness Squadron fuels distribution quality assurance inspector, carries a fuel line hose during Forward Area Refueling Point team tryouts @moody_afb, Ga. The FARP team is made up of Airmen from the 23d LRS Petroleum, Oils and Lubricants flight that are responsible for providing needed fuel to aircraft in a rapid manner. In order to become fully qualified, FARP team members must undergo a rigorous amount of continuous physical and mental training to ensure they’re fit for duty. Following the tryouts the Airmen were interviewed to further evaluate their mental readiness to join the FARP team and ultimately one Airman was chosen. 
.
📸  by Airman 1st Class Eugene Oliver

node.text:
In good hands 🩹 
.
1st Lt. Rylyn Kinoshita and Staff. Sgt. Ebony Davis, 624th Regional Support Group Reserve Citizen Airmen, trained on medical scenarios in a blood lab during Pacific Warriorz 2021 at Schofield Barracks, Hawaii. The Total Force Integration and Joint Training exercise utilizes a blood lab to allow technicians to treat injuries with fake blood, loud sounds and fog which simulates a combat environment. 
.
📸 by James Bowman
